  explanation:
    "This mantra encapsulates the three core principles of Dojo practice. 'I accept what is' reflects the acceptance-based processing that prevents error signals from escalating into suffering. Acceptance does not mean approval or passivity -- it means acknowledging reality as it is, including errors, discomfort, and imperfection, without adding a layer of resistance that amplifies the original distress. When you accept what is, you free the ACC to process errors as information rather than threats, which is the foundation of calibrated responding.\n\n'I calibrate what arises' speaks to the active, skillful work of adjusting your response to match the actual demands of the situation. Calibration is the bridge between acceptance and action. You accept the error signal, then you tune your response so it is proportionate and effective. 'The struggle itself is the meaning' addresses the inevitable question of why bother. In the Dojo framework, the difficulty of practice is not an obstacle to overcome on the way to some future reward -- it is the practice itself. Every moment of struggle, every noticed distraction, every accepted error is a repetition that strengthens the neural circuits of calibration. Use this mantra at the start of your Morning Protocol, repeating it silently three times, letting each phrase settle before moving to the next. Return to it throughout the day whenever you notice the urge to react rather than respond.",
